le="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">urther </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">ducation </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">olleges, we </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">remind the Committee that Ofsted inspects colleges </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">it assesses as being in need of an inspection, for example, if results have declined</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. It is therefore highly likely that </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">a large</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">amount</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">good</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">outstanding</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> teaching and learning</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> in colleges is not inspected.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">There is a growing concern</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> that lesson observation as a means to judge the overall quality of teaching and learning is unreliable</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> because o</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">bservation ratings </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">can</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> be </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">consistent</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">we welcome Ofsted’s </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">decision</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to include, for example, student feedback and wider learning</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">, r</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">eports </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">colleges</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">suggest </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">there </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> still too many conclusions drawn from lesson observation alone.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The Social and Economic imperative</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.4pt; padding-left:4.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">We note the Chief Inspector’s comments about how the education system is failing to make a difference to the achievement of the most disadvantaged young people. Only 36% of young people eligible for free school meals gained five GCSEs at grades A*-C compared with 63% of other pupils</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. The Chief Inspector asks FE and skills providers to “break the link between deprivation and poor life chances”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.  However we make the following points:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.21pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Local authorities rarely tell colleges which of the young people they </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">enrol</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> received free school meals whilst in school despite there being no legal barriers to prevent this information being shared. As a result</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> colleges cannot identify and monitor these young people after the age of 16. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.21pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">We do not believe that Ofsted have the metrics to determine whether FE is making a difference to the lives of the most deprived. They use Level 3 value added data produced by the Department for Education which includes the achievement of students who have spent year</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> 12</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> in a school and then either dropped out or continued at a college. The same data does not </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">penalise</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> schools for drop-out. If Ofsted are to encourage a step change in supporting achievement for the most deprived, they should ensure that tracking is effective and that where a difference is being made, everyone understands how.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.21pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">We have welcomed Ofsted’s emphasi</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">s,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> since September 2012</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> on teaching, learning and assessment and monitoring of progress and progression to work and higher education. However, </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> inspection methodology is still too focused on qualification success rates. There must be incentives to recruit students who have </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">spent time </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">not in employment, education </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">or</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> training and those </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">from</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> the most difficult social and economic backgrounds</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">GCSE English and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">maths</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> achievement</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">nnual </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">eport is very critical of English and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">maths</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> provision in colleges</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">he vast majority of young people who do not achieve an A*-C </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">grade </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">in English and </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">maths</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">by</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> 16</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> go to college when they leave school</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The Report</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">criticises</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> the fact that 40% of young people achieve</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">maths</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> GCSE at college when they have fai</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">led at school and 33% achieve</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> English GCSE. Many would see this as laudable when colleges have two years to rectify 11 year years of failure in school.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Whereas GCSEs were once considered a gateway to employment and A Levels, they are now considered to be achievable by all. Whilst no one in colleges doubts the importance of </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">maths</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and English skills for future employment, Ofsted’s focus on GCSE does not </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> how effectively students learn </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">maths</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> and English skills in the context of a subject they find motivating. We feel that there needs to be an appreciation that colleges are building their capacity to address the policy that </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">emphasises</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> GCSE as a preferred route and that Ofsted must </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> this to avoid </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">demotivating</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">colleges </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">as they work hard to find solutions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Preparing young people to progress to employment </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The report </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">criticises</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> colleges’ responsiveness to employers’ need and cites a case study from Bristol which judges only 20% of college provision to be matched to Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) priorities. This raises a number of issues:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">very little data is supp</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">lied to support this criticism</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">the methodology for ‘matching’ qualifications to priority employment areas is not described – with many qualifications which are soon to be termed ‘applied general’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> it is hard to discern which priority area they are directly linked to as students will progress to many different employment sectors from them;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">evidence from many sources</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> demonstrates that the ability of LEPs to determine skills priorities is, at best, variable, and yet this is the only source used as the basis of the Chief Inspector’s criticism;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">Colleges are keen to ensure that they meet the needs of local employers, but local circumstances are so varied that some find it </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">extremely difficult</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> to have a voice, for example, on local LEP boards</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">;</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">even if local priorities are correctly identified and local LEP arrangements are functioning well, there is, as yet, no indication of how many local jobs will be found </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">exclusively in those priority areas. It may be that 20% is an acceptable figure in an area seeking to grow certain areas, but where the bulk of skills required remain in more traditional areas of work. Ofsted need to recognise that some colleges have national as well as local perspective and have LEP and council priorities which may be different. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Careers Guidance</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> mismatch between t</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">he curriculum and skills needs will</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> require a significant focus on careers guidance in both schools and colleges</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">We are disappointed that</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> there have been only minor changes in Ofsted’s school inspection guidance</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">. We believe only schools with </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">good</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">outstanding</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">careers guidance </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">should</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> receive a </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">good</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">outstanding</span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt"> grade for </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">their </span><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">overall effectiveness. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Palatino; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"